@KELLI KELLI No state is phasing them out. You may see an individual city phase them out where they can transition customers to sewer systems, such as Jacksonville (in a Republican run state...) but it is impossible for any US state to phase them out. No state has a large enough budget to do so.

But to make sure I didn't miss some state stupidly trying to regulate against reality, I checked - EVERY. SINGLE. ONE. of the Democrat run states. Washington, Oregon, California, Nevada, New Mexico, Colorado, Illinois, New York, Vermont, Maine, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland, and Virginia are not doing anything that you could even confuse for "phasing out" septic. Hawaii is phasing out home sewage discharge (which is insane that it hadn't already been done), not septic.

They certainly do regulate septic systems (or "on site system" as many of those state regulators I just looked through label it) but every single US state allows septic tanks and no US state has implemented a phase-out of septic.

