@Merennulli fair, and I agree that approach would logically make sense if the tech could be made to work. 
It did just make me consider something different though now. The testing chemicals are now after performing the test, presumably been flushed with the rest of the sewage. Sure it's only a few ml at a time, but repeat over 50000 or more homes and you rapidly have large numbers of a new chemical in the sewage that treatment plants need to deal with. Have to wonder if that will increase the costs, possibly not but it is something that would need to be considered.

Honestly once everything is taken into account, I really doubt that you could get enough usable information out of these tests (even if they could tell you every single thing that was in the sewage) to make it cost effective in the current world. But then give it a while and you never know if there could be a market for it, atleast on a small scale to test an "average" neighbourhood.

